
  <sn><md>### SOIL QUALITY{.text-center}

#### Define Soil Quality

Soil quality is a measure of the ++capacity or ability++ of a soil to `perform necessary functions`.


Soil functions include

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**Enviroment**
- filtering and cleaning water
- regulating temperature
- recycling and storing nutrients
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**Organism**
- providing nutrients and water to plants and 
- providing habitats for organisms
:::
:::


**Doran and Parkin (1994)** defined soil quality as, 'the capacity of a soil to function, within ecosystem and land use boundaries, to sustain productivity, maintain environmental quality and promote plant and animal health.'<br>
Soil quality reflects a combination of physical, chemical and biological properties.

![diagram](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/Soil-quality-dgrm-1.png)

**Soil quality is of two types. They are-**

- **a.** Inherent Soil Quality
- **b.** Dynamic Soil Quality

:::.row

**Inherent Soil Quality**: The inherent soil quality is defined as the aspects of soil quality `relating to a soil's natural composition and properties` influenced by the `factors and processes` of soil formation, in the `absence of human` impacts. {.col-12 .col-md-6 .px-2}

**Dynamic Soil Quality**: Dynamic soil quality relates to soil properties that `change as a result of soil use and management` over the human time scale. {.col-12 .col-md-6 .px-2}

:::
</md></sn>
